==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*frijōn-'', from Indo-European ''*prāy-, *prēy-''.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[friehan]] (Dutch [[vrijen]]), Old High Norse [[fria]] ‘free’, [[frjá]] ‘love’ (Norwegian [[fria]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐍂𐌹𐌾𐍉𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πραυς]], Slavonic ''*prьjatī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[прити]], Russian [[приять]] ‘friend’), Old Irish [[ríar]] (Welsh [[rhydd]] ‘free’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'fɹe:ojan/

===Verb===
'''frēoġan''' (class 2 weak)
# to [[free]], to [[liberate]]
#:''Freo hine on ðam seofoðan geare'': free him in the seventh year.  (Deuteronomy)
# to [[like]], to [[love]], to [[honour]]
#:''Ic ðec for sunu wylle freogan'': I will love you as a son.  (''Beowulf'')

